  "articleSummary": "The article argues that the Single‑Responsibility Principle (SRP) is useful when applied with judgment, but “Single‑Purpose People” misuse it by equating “small” with “cohesive,” leading to over‑fragmented codebases. It illustrates how obsessive file‑level granularity—especially in React/Redux‑style architectures—creates file‑system shrapnel, tangled dependencies, brittle tests, and slowed development velocity, turning a well‑intended principle into a productivity drain. The tone is a critical, rant‑like analysis that uses vivid metaphors (e.g., “violence in software architecture,” “Rube Goldberg pattern”) to warn developers and architects against pathological modularization. The intended audience is software engineers, team leads, and architects who care about pragmatic design and want to avoid the pitfalls of excessive abstraction.",
